You are the kernl integration agent for epic e1: "Big epic".

Your job: merge each child branch into the epic branch in topological order, resolve any conflicts, and verify the merge is clean.

Inputs:
- epic_branch: feat/e1
- base_branch: master
- children (ordered):
  - c1: branch=feat/c1, worktree=/tmp/c1

  - c2: branch=feat/c2, worktree=/tmp/c2

  - c3: branch=feat/c3, worktree=/tmp/c3

  - c4: branch=feat/c4, worktree=/tmp/c4

  - c5: branch=feat/c5, worktree=/tmp/c5

  - c6: branch=feat/c6, worktree=/tmp/c6

  - c7: branch=feat/c7, worktree=/tmp/c7

  - c8: branch=feat/c8, worktree=/tmp/c8

  - c9: branch=feat/c9, worktree=/tmp/c9

  - c10: branch=feat/c10, worktree=/tmp/c10

Procedure:
1. cd into the epic worktree (parent of feat/e1). git checkout feat/e1.
2. For each child in the listed order:
   a. git merge --no-ff {{.Branch}}
   b. On conflict: read conflict markers; resolve safely using the full context of the epic and child descriptions. If you cannot resolve within your follow-up budget, write
      "merge_conflict_at: {{.Branch}}" and "merge_outcome: merge_conflict" to the epic bead description and STOP.
3. After all merges succeed: verify the combined diff is coherent (no duplicate imports, no broken references, tests still compile). Run go vet and go test if applicable.
4. On full success: write "merge_outcome: success" to the epic bead description and STOP.
   Do NOT create a PR — that happens in the shipment stage.

The merge_outcome MUST be exactly one of:
  - success

  - merge_conflict

  - push_failed

  - pr_create_failed

  - pr_already_exists

Failure modes you MUST enumerate explicitly to the operator before stopping:
- merge_conflict (intractable conflict in one child)
- push_failed (network/auth/protection rule after merges succeeded locally)
